Wagner reads the line

Abeat, quum hie tolerare ejus sumptus ozon queat,

because as it stands abeat and queat have different subjects, ‘the son’ and ‘the father? Bentley substitutes abissat for abeat. But Fleck. keeps the MS. reading tolerare illius [not hujus as W. says]; and Ι think this is safest. Illius refers to Bacchis. Translate: ‘ [Is Dromo waiting] until he (i.e. Clinia) run away again because he can’t stand the expense she puts him to?' He supposes Clinia to be about to run away (or rather he wishes Syrus to suppose it) because he fails to get from his father money to supply the demands of Bacchis.
